[6] UK (Nottingham)
Date: Wed 13 Apr 2011
Source: This is Nottingham [summ., edited]
http://www.thisisnottingham.co.uk/news/Immunisation-warning-measles-cases-city/article-3440058-detail/article.html


Immunisation warning after measles cases in city
------------------------------------------------
Parents are being urged to get their children immunised after cases
of measles were reported in the city. NHS [National Health Service]
Nottingham City, which pays for and plans healthcare in Nottingham, is
still failing to meet its targets for the number of children aged 5
and under having the MMR vaccine -- which protects against measles,
mumps, and rubella.

Last year [2010], 83.3 per cent of children in the city had had the
MMR vaccine by their 2nd birthday -- against a target of 95 per cent.
The number of children who had received the MMR booster by their 5th
birthday was also below the 95 per cent target at 82.3 per cent.
However, the proportion of children who have been immunised in general
has been increasing.

"Vaccinations are sometimes not seen as a priority by some people,"
said Caroline Jordan, senior public health nurse for NHS Nottingham
City. "That's despite GPs' repeated phone calls and letters. Sometimes
people don't understand the importance of vaccination. Some may be
unsure what their child has had, particularly if they have come from
another country. "We do know there's some measles circulating at the
moment that further promotes the need for children to be up to date
with their vaccinations.

"Measles is a particularly infectious disease which can give
unpleasant symptoms with high temperatures, a rash, as well as aches
and pains. Miss Jordan said she believed part of the increase in the
uptake was due to GPs encouraging parents.

[byline: Claire Carter]

