[8] Australia (Victoria)
Date: Sat 16 Apr 2011
Source: 7 News, Australian Associated Press (AAP) report [edited]
http://au.news.yahoo.com/a/-/latest/9208842/measles-alert-issued-in-victoria/


Measles alert issued in Victoria
--------------------------------
A measles alert has been issued in Victoria after 4 passengers who
arrived in Melbourne on an Air Asia flight from Malaysia this month
[April 2011] were detected with the disease. The flight arrived from
Kuala Lumpur in Melbourne on the morning of 1 Apr 2011. One case was
identified at the Austin Hospital on 14 Apr 2011. As a precaution,
patients who attended the Austin's emergency department between 9am
and 7.30pm (AEST) on Thu 14 Apr 2011 are being contacted by hospital
staff. The Victorian Health Department says more than 90 per cent of
attendees have been telephoned so far, and about half of those have
been asked to return this weekend for a measles vaccination. Another
suspected case is recovering in an interstate hospital.

Victoria's chief health officer John Carnie said that while the 4
patients are now recovering, it is possible there may be others who
were infected on the flight. Dr Carnie said the illness usually begins
with common cold symptoms such as fever, sore throat, red eyes, and a
cough. The rash usually begins 3 to 7 days after the 1st symptoms,
generally starting on the face and then spreading to the rest of the
body. "Measles is a highly infectious viral disease that can cause
serious illness, particularly in very young children and adults," Dr
Carnie said. Immunisation is the best defence against measles because
anyone unvaccinated is at risk of contracting the disease, he said.

Anyone developing symptoms is advised to ring ahead to their GP or
hospital first and tell them that they have fever and a rash. The
Health Department advises that anyone who has been in contact with a
measles case should also alert their GP or hospital emergency
department. Adults aged between 26 and 42 years have a lower
immunisation coverage than younger adults and children and therefore
most cases are in this age group. Most people over the age of 42 will
have been exposed to measles in childhood and will be protected. Dr
Carnie said measles is particularly serious in people who are
undergoing cancer treatment or are on high-dose steroids, even if they
have had measles or have been immunised against measles. The measles
vaccine is currently recommended on the National Immunisation Program
for children aged 12 months and 4 years.

