[9] New Zealand (Hawke's Bay)
Date:: Tue 12 Apr 2011
Source: Hawke's Bay Today [edited]
http://www.hawkesbaytoday.co.nz/local/news/hawkes-bay-measles-outbreak-worsens/3947990/


Hawke's Bay measles outbreak worsens
------------------------------------
Three more cases of measles have been confirmed by Hawke's Bay
District Health Board, bringing the total to 9. The new cases were
children who had been in isolation waiting to see if they developed
measles, and were all linked to the earlier cases.

On Friday [8 Apr 2011] the Hawke's Bay District Health Board
confirmed 6 cases of measles in Hastings -- the 1st 2 linked to
confirmed cases in Auckland, and the others secondary to the Hastings
cases. All 9 children were from a Flaxmere school and none was
admitted to hospital. Medical officer of health Caroline McElnay said
public health nurses had been in touch with those who may have been
exposed, but she was hopeful no new cases would develop.

Parents were asked to keep sick children at home, and schools to keep
sick children away, in the hope of limiting the spread of the highly
contagious viral infection. The outbreak prompted a warning from
Plunket's clinical adviser Allison Jamieson about vaccinations. She
said vaccination was the most effective form of preventing childhood
illnesses such as measles, for which there was no treatment. It was
easily spread through the air by breathing, coughing, and sneezing.

"Immunisation has a profoundly positive effect not only on the
individual but on the whole of the population, thereby improving
community immunity from the disease," Ms Jamieson said. "It is never
too late to catch up, even if a child has fallen behind on the
immunisation schedule." Children over one year -- who had not had 2
doses of measles vaccine in the past, were eligible for the free MMR
vaccine.

Although most infected people would not need hospitalisation,
complications could arise. The Ministry of Health estimated about one
in 10 cases developed into pneumonia, ear infection, or diarrhoea. One
in 1000 cases got inflammation of the brain, which could lead to
permanent brain damage or even death.

Dr McElnay said measles cases were rare in Hawke's Bay and the last
known was in 2009. This year [2011] the Auckland Regional Public
Health Service reported 24 confirmed cases from between mid-January
and early March. None of the 24 people confirmed with measles had been
vaccinated against it.

The last epidemic of measles in New Zealand was in 1997 when about
2000 people, mostly babies and children, were infected, with more than
300 people needing hospital care. Before immunisation began in 1969,
almost all children caught measles.

[byline: Jolene Williams]

