[10] New Zealand (Hawke's Bay)
Date: Fri 15 Apr 2011
Source: Hawke's Bay Today [edited]
http://www.hawkesbaytoday.co.nz/local/news/hawkes-bay-measles-outbreak-12-cases-confirmed/3948440/


Hawke's Bay measles outbreak: 12 cases confirmed
------------------------------------------------
Three more children have contracted measles and more are in isolation
in their homes as the outbreak spreads among a small community group
in Flaxmere. The new confirmed cases brings the total to 12, but that
may rise as Hawke's Bay District Health Board [HBDHB] staff wait to
see whether those in isolation develop the viral infection.

The infected children attend the same Flaxmere school and those in
isolation are from the same community group. Those being isolated had
come into contact with the infected people and were not immune. None
of the infected children were in hospital.

HBDHB public health nurses were in daily contact with those infected,
their school and those in isolation. Medical officer of health
Caroline McElnay said the containment measures had been in place since
the 1st cases became known late last week [week of 4 Apr 2011]. "We're
pretty confident at this stage that we've got it under control, but we
have to see what happens next. Hopefully, we've managed to [contain
the infection] in time and well enough," she said.

Dr McElnay said the cluster of cases was a timely reminder for people
aged under 42, who had not previously had measles, to check the
vaccination status of themselves and their children. The MMR
vaccination was the only form of prevention and health authorities
advised two jabs to give the best chance of immunity. The vaccination
is offered to 15 month old babies and at age 4, but is free for anyone
over 1 and born after 1969 who have not already had 2 jabs.

Dr McElnay urged parents to keep sick children at home, even over the
school holidays. Measles was highly contagious and symptoms initially
mirrored a typical cold. Infected people could experience a runny
nose, cough, irritated eyes, sore throat, and fever, but within 2 to 4
days a rash would appear and spread around the body. "Most children
are miserable and stay in bed, drink lots of fluids, and are fine, but
1 in 10 may need future treatment and end up in hospital." Serious
complications could develop and prove fatal.

[byline: Jolene Williams]

