[11] Canada (Saskatchewan)
Date: Mon 18 Apr 2011
Source: globalsaskatoon.com, The Regina Leader-Post report [summ.,
edited]
http://www.globalsaskatoon.com/health/regina+appelle+health+region+confirms+cases+measles/4623444/story.html


Regina Qu'Appelle Health Region confirms 2 cases of measles
-----------------------------------------------------------
Two cases of measles have been confirmed in Regina, adding "there has
been potential exposure in other parts of the province."

The 1st case was found in a 9 month old infant on 2 or 3 Apr 2011,
said the Regina Qu'Appelle Health Region's deputy medical health
officer, Dr Maurice Hennick. The 2nd case developed in a 3 year old
household member of the infant. "Patient one is doing very well and
recovering and patient 2 is quite ill," said Hennick. As of Friday [15
Apr 2011], both patients were at home, resting.

Saskatchewan deputy chief medical health officer Dr Saquib Shahab
said the cases are significant enough that the public should be
notified. "We'll be watching very closely over the next several weeks
to see if we get any secondary cases," said Shahab.

A media release said people who were in the waiting area the Pasqua
Hospital's emergency room (ER) on 3 Apr 2011 from 1:30-3:30 pm, on 4
Apr 2011 from 9:30-11:30 am, or 5 Apr 2011 from 1- 3 pm are
"especially cautioned to watch for the appearance of measles."

Hennick said measles is an unusual occurrence in the province. The
last confirmed case was in 2005. "Measles has complications and
certainly can be quite a severe illness," said Hennick. The virus can
cause ear infections, pneumonia, and brain infections in all ages.

There is a 75 per cent voluntary vaccination rate for measles. On
standard cases, a child gets an initial vaccine shot at 12 months and
a 2nd shot at 18 months. Hennick said the 9 month old was obviously
not vaccinated, but the 3 year old had one shot. "We've done extensive
investigations around the possible origins of where this may have
arisen," said Hennick. "That is not clear at this stage and we are
doing further steps to see if we can identify that."

Parents can call the health ministry's HealthLine at 1-877-800-0002
for advice. If visiting a doctor or emergency room, it is recommended
that you call in advance so that the child can be seen in a separate
area without exposing others.

Parents of children one year and older who are not up to date with
immunization are encouraged to call their local public health office
to arrange for vaccination. The public is reminded that measles is
occurring sporadically in Europe, some parts of the USA, and several
cases have also been reported from Quebec and British Columbia in the
past few months. People should ensure they are up to date with all
vaccines prior to travel. If any member of the public is unsure if
they have their shots, they can call their local health region.

[byline: Taylor Shire]

