[13] USA (Rhode Island ex Italy)
Date: Fri 15 Apr 2011
Source: projo.com, The Providence Journal [edited]
http://newsblog.projo.com/2011/04/measles-an-unusual-visitor-sho.html


Measles, an unusual visitor, shows up in Rhode Island
-----------------------------------------------------
A case of measles, a highly contagious disease that is considered
eradicated in the United States, cropped up in Rhode Island on
Wednesday [13 Apr 2011], according to the state Department of Health.
The patient is a woman in her 20s from Italy who arrived in New York
from that country on Tuesday [12 Apr 2011], said Annemarie
Beardsworth, public information officer for the department. After she
traveled by car to Rhode Island, she sought medical assistance, and
"an astute physician" informed the Department of Health that a
potential case of measles was at hand. A blood test confirmed the
diagnosis.

Measles is an ancient scourge, one of several diseases that Europeans
are thought to have introduced inadvertently to the New World -- one
that decimated the population of Native Americans, who had no
immunity. It can be prevented via the measles, mumps, and rubella
[MMR] vaccine that is standard for American schoolchildren.

The virus can kill. Beardsworth said children are especially
vulnerable, as are individuals with health problems. Beardsworth said
it has been at least 20 years since Rhode Island saw a case of
measles. She said the Department of Health quickly notified
surrounding states and the US Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention. She said the federal agency is working with airport
officials in New York to track passengers who were on the same flight
and ensure they are up to date on the vaccine. It is recommended that
the vaccine be applied within 72 hours of exposure.

Beardsworth said the patient is in voluntary isolation and has been
"extremely cooperative" and is "doing fine." "The quick response by
the physician" and staff of the Department of Health prevented the
disease from spreading in Rhode Island, Michael Fine, interim director
of the Department of Health, said in a news release. Beardsworth said
the department had identified only about 20 Rhode Islanders who might
have been exposed.

[byline: Thomas J Morgan]

